data.content:
Use EF Core 7+'s **`ExecuteUpdateAsync`** and **`ExecuteDeleteAsync`**. These translate directly to SQL `UPDATE`/`DELETE` — no entities loaded into memory:

```csharp
// Operation 1: Bulk update — single UPDATE statement
await _db.Products
    .Where(p => p.LastSoldDate < DateTime.UtcNow.AddMonths(-6))
    .ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
        s.SetProperty(p => p.IsActive, false));

// Operation 2: Bulk delete — single DELETE statement
await _db.AuditLogs
    .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < DateTime.UtcNow.AddYears(-1))
    .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
```

**Why this is fast:**
- Your original code fetches 500K/2M rows into memory, tracks them all, then sends individual `UPDATE`/`DELETE` statements back
- These generate a **single SQL statement** executed server-side — no data leaves the database

**Caveats:**
- These bypass change tracking — any already-loaded entities won't reflect the changes. Call after or instead of `SaveChangesAsync`, not mixed with tracked changes
- No `SaveChangesAsync()` needed — they execute immediately
- If 2M deletes in one transaction causes lock escalation, batch with a loop:

```csharp
int deleted;
do
{
    deleted = await _db.AuditLogs
        .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < DateTime.UtcNow.AddYears(-1))
        .Take(10_000)
        .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
} while (deleted > 0);
```
